  "created": "2025-10-15",
  "description": "Cell division in E. coli is initiated by assembly of the FtsZ ring (Z-ring) at the future division site (midcell). FtsZ is a tubulin-like GTPase that polymerizes into protofilaments which bundle to form a contractile ring structure. Z-ring placement is controlled by the Min system (oscillates pole-to-pole, inhibiting FtsZ at poles) and nucleoid occlusion (Noc/SlmA prevents division over unsegregated chromosomes). Once positioned, FtsZ recruits over 30 other divisome proteins in a hierarchical order: early arrivals (FtsA, ZipA stabilize Z-ring), middle arrivals (FtsK, FtsQ, FtsL, FtsB), and late arrivals (FtsW, FtsI for peptidoglycan synthesis). The coordinated action of these proteins drives septal peptidoglycan synthesis, membrane constriction, and cell separation. This flowchart illustrates the complete pathway from Z-ring assembly site selection through divisome maturation and cytokinesis.",
  "id": "ecoli_cell_division",
